                                                                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="14470878" author="blackdrag" created="Fri, 18 Feb 2011 09:59:21 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;what is a scenario in which you have a binding per session, but no single threaded access to that per session binding?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14470807" author="ujay68" created="Fri, 18 Feb 2011 15:03:17 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;jochen, i was thinking of a java web application (a typical combination of servlets, jsp, portlets, whatever...) and that application also uses groovy scripts for plug-ins and extensibility. a user might log into that application and get an authenticated session (javax.servlet.http.HttpSession). now it could be useful to have one Binding per http session, so that different scripts inside that application have a common scope, as long as they are invoked for the same session. even if there is typically only one session per authenticated user, the user&apos;s browser will run many http requests in parallel resulting in parallel threads accessing the same binding. (in such a scenario, of course all objects shared between threads must be thread-safe, but that is something the application must do.) -jay&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14470846" author="blackdrag" created="Fri, 18 Feb 2011 15:26:59 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;but wouldn&apos;t it be reasonable to use a custom binding in that case then?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14470865" author="ujay68" created="Fri, 18 Feb 2011 15:42:56 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;i&apos;m not deep enough into groovy&apos;s architecture to judge what the best way would be, but if Binding is not thread-safe by intention, i suggest the javadoc say so (and this would be a documentation issue only &lt;img class=&quot;emoticon&quot; src=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/images/icons/emoticons/smile.png&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot; align=&quot;absmiddle&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;/&gt;. -jay&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14470827" author="ujay68" created="Fri, 18 Feb 2011 15:44:56 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;btw, if you use groovy through the javax.script package, is there a way to use a custom binding?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14470810" author="guillaume" created="Fri, 25 Feb 2011 09:59:23 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The Binding is not intended to be used in a multithreaded context (I&apos;ll add a note in the JavaDoc about it).&lt;br/&gt;
If you need that, you can always extend the Binding class to cover your needs.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
